## List rendering — stable composite keys

Never use `key={i}` (array index) for lists whose content can change.
Use a stable composite key derived from the item's content:

```tsx
// ❌ Unstable — causes jank when list updates
{lines.map((line, i) => <div key={i} ...>)}

// ✅ Stable composite key
{lines.map((line) => (
  <div key={`${line.lineNumber}-${line.type}`} ...>
))}
```

Index keys are only acceptable for **static** arrays that never reorder or change
length (e.g. a fixed list of format options rendered once).

For secret values (passwords, passphrases, API keys), use a positional prefix —
never use the secret value itself as the React key:

```tsx
// ✅ positional prefix
{passwords.map((pw, i) => <div key={`pw-${i}`} ...>)}

// ❌ exposes secret in React internals
{passwords.map((pw) => <div key={pw} ...>)}
```

For non-sensitive unique IDs (UUID, ULID, NanoId), the value itself is the stable key:
```tsx
{uuids.map((id) => <div key={id} ...>)}  // ✅ UUIDs are unique and non-sensitive
```

